difference between 2.7.0 and 2.8.1

incompatible changes

* #1761: moments created without a language are no longer following the global language, in case it changes. Only newly created moments take the global language by default. In case you're affected by this, wait, comment on #1797 and wait for a proper reimplementation
* #1642: 45 days is no longer "a month" according to humanize, cutoffs for month, and year have changed. Hopefully your code does not depend on a particular answer from humanize (which it shouldn't anyway)
* #1784: if you use the human readable English datetime format in a weird way (like storing them in a database) that would break when the format changes you're at risk.
* #1785  moment.momentProperties  is now an array of properties instead of a hash. If you have a plugin that uses it to make sure cloned moments will retain the plugin-added properties you need to change your code.

deprecations (old behavior will be dropped in 3.0)

* #1761  lang  is renamed to  locale ,  langData  ->  localeData . Also there is now defineLocale  that should be used when creating new locales
* #1763  add(unit, value)  and  subtract(unit, value)  are now deprecated. Use  add(value, unit)  and  subtract(value, unit)  instead.
* #1759 rename  duration.toIsoString  to  duration.toISOString . The js standard library and moment's  toISOString  follow that convention.

new locales

* #1789 Tibetan (bo)
* #1786 Africaans (af)
* #1778 Burmese (my)
* #1727 Belarusian (be)

bugfixes

* #1738 local to zone conversion with keepLocalTime=true
* #1642 more accurate humanize

performance

* #1808 speedup cloning 49x
* #1708 speedup creation with Date object

features

*#1716  moment.relativeTimeThreshold  now supports getting the existing threshold

locale bugfix

* #1784 add comma between day-of-month and year in us-en
* #1710 fix lithuanian month name

2.8.1

* bugfix #1813: fix moment().lang([key]) incompatibility

Correctly propagate InterruptedExceptions.

Summary:
Buck handles client disconnections by interupting the command
processing thread, unfortunately a number of exception handlers would
swallow the generated InterruptedExceptions resulting in command
execution to continue when it should have halted. This mostly
mechanical refactoring removes the erroneous InterruptedException
catch blocks and adds InterruptedException to the list of exceptions
thrown by affected methods. Where this is not possible due to the
method signature being defined by a system interface, the interruption
is propagated using Thread.currentThread().interrupt() which is the
correct way to preserve state when propagating interruptions.

Ensure we print buck.py stderr to logs

Summary:
Currently, `ProjectBuildFileParser` ensures it writes
buck.py's stderr to `Console`, but nothing ensures stderr goes to the
logs.

I've been working on improving `buck.py`'s `glob()` method, and it was
really difficult to diagnose problems via Buck's debug logs.

To help with that, this diff introduces an optional delegate
`InputStreamConsumer.Handler` which allows users of
`InputStreamConsumer` to get a callback for each line of input.

I use the delegate from `ProjectBuildFileParser` to log a warning
to the debug logs for each line printed by buck.py to stderr.

(Unlike error logs, we do not send warning logs to the console -- only
to the debug logs on disk.)

ProcessExecutor: Extend to allow faking out launching processes

Summary:
I'm implementing a warning if the IDE is open when running
'buck project'. To write the tests, I needed a testable version of
`java.lang.ProcessBuilder`.

Unfortunately, `ProcessBuilder` doesn't have a way to fake out the
processes it builds from actually being launched.

So, I split its
job into `ProcessExecutorParams` (an immutable value type and Builder) and added another set of methods to `ProcessExecutor` which takes a `ProcessExecutorParams` describing a process to be launched instead of an already-launched `Process`.

Fix ProcessExecutor so it doesn't print empty strings on process failure

Summary:
I noticed an earlier diff caused SuperConsole to stop printing output,
even when nothing was printed to the console (which I added in a followup
diff).

I added debug logging and found a bug: ProcessExecutor calls
`OutputStream.print("")` if the process does not exit cleanly, even if
the process prints nothing to stdout or stderr.

Since calling `print()` on `DirtyPrintStreamDecorator` has the side
effect of causing SuperConsole to cease updating, this is pretty bad.
(It means any time we pass a process to `ProcessExecutor` and it fails
silently, we stop the console completely.)

This diff fixes the bug and adds a test which reproduces the bug and confirms
the fix.

Test Plan:
Unit test included.
Ran `ant java-test -Dtest.class=ProcessExecutorTest` before fix, confirmed
it failed. Applied fix, repeated test, confirmed it passed.

Add timeout support `ShellStep` and use it for `JUnitStep`

Summary:
Previously, we've been relying on an in-house timeout we've added
to `JUnitRunner` which essentially cleans up timed out threads use
`Thread.interrupt()`.  This has been causing problems recently
since it's relying on the timed out thread to periodically perform
some operation to check the interrupt flag, and it's common that
this doesn't happen.  Furthermore, the test process could get stuck
in various other ways (calling into native code?) which could prevent
it from properly timing itself diff.

Rather than having the test process police itself, this diff adds a
timeout to the `ShellStep` class and has `JUnitStep` use this rather
passing a timeout down into the junit runner.  In the event of a time-
out, a special result file is touch so that the result interpreter
knows to signify a timeout to the user.

One down side is that now the timeout applies to the whole test,
rather than individual test classes within the single java_test.  I
think this is reasonable.  If we really want to support per-test class
timeouts, we should be doing what more advanced test runners do and
have buck manage and schedule each individual test class/method on its
own, rather than delegating to a black box test runner (e.g. `JUnitRunner`).

This diff also makes it a bit easier for other languages to add time-
outs to their testing support (e.g. python, C++), since this style is
language/framework independent.

Test Plan: Added a spinning java_test to verify we correctly time this out.

Update JUnitRunner to include java.util.logging messages in stdout / stderr

Summary:
Currently, `JUnitRunner` plays tricks with `System.out` and `System.err`.
That means all log messages written to the standard `java.util.logging` are lost
even if we properly set up logging.

This diff explicitly registers a log `Handler` with `java.util.logging`
before each test to write test log data to the redirected `System.out` and
`System.err` so we can get more information about what happened when a test
fails.
